• Stress level¶

• Tonic EDA - long term changes¶

What can you do?¶

• EDA is correlated with Autonomous Nervous System (ANS)¶

• Level of attention¶

• Cognitive load¶

eda_data_subset = eda_data.set_index('timestamp')

However, the timestamps will be printed one on top of the other.

Filtering¶

The raw EDA data is not ideal to work on. This can be due to factors such as artifacts in the signals, e.g., sudden movements. As such, it is appropriate to apply some filters.

For EDA data, we shall apply a 1st Order Butterworth filter, with a cutoff frequency of 0.4Hz.

Why this specific filter? Researchers from the literature, in similar scenarios, have found it appropriate. Later we'll show what changes with different filters. 🤔

Butterworth filter [4]¶

• Mathematically complicated filter¶

• Designed to have maintain signal strength across different frequencies¶

• It maintains the "passband" (important part of the signal) unchanged as much as possible¶

• We just remove the noise¶

In [7]:
filtered_data: ndarray = butter_lowpass_filter_filtfilt(
                            data=eda_data_subset['EDA'], 
                            fs=4, 
                            cutoff=0.4,
                            order=1)
eda_data_subset['filt-EDA'] = filtered_data

Let's see the difference!

In [8]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,3))
plt.plot(eda_data_subset['timestamp'].values, 
         eda_data_subset['EDA'].values, '-', 
         color='blue', alpha=0.6)
plt.plot(eda_data_subset['timestamp'].values, 
         eda_data_subset['filt-EDA'].values, '-', 
         color='red', alpha=0.6)
plt.xticks(rotation=30)
plt.xlabel("Timestamp")
plt.ylabel("EDA (μS)")
plt.title("EDA values over time")
plt.show()

Normalization¶

• Different users have different responses¶

• Interpersonal variability¶

• How to deal with this issue?¶

Normalization → remove interpersonal differences¶

Let's look at how the ranges differ for our users

In [13]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(14, 3))
total_max = max(eda_data['EDA'])
total_min = min(eda_data['EDA'])
for ax, usr, col in zip(axs, 
                        list(eda_data['username'].unique()), 
                        ['red', 'blue']):
    ax.plot(eda_data[eda_data['username'] == usr]['EDA'].values, 
            '-', color=col)
    ax.set_xlabel("Timestamp")
    ax.set_ylabel("EDA (μS)")
    ax.set_title(f"User {usr}")
    ax.set_ylim(total_min, total_max)
plt.show()

Define a function to perform the normalization

In [14]:
import numpy as np
def normalize_signals(x: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:
    """
    This method takes as input an array and perform the normalization (min-max) over it.
    
    Args:
        x (ndarray): input array

    Returns:
        (ndarray): array normalized

    """
    max_val: float = np.max(x)
    min_val: float = np.min(x)
    return (x - min_val)/(max_val - min_val)

The normalization has to be applied on each different user's data.

But we need to first filter the data for both users.

In [15]:
filtered_data: ndarray = [
    butter_lowpass_filter_filtfilt(
    data=eda_data[eda_data['username'] == user]['EDA'], 
    fs=4, 
    cutoff=0.4,
    order=1,)
    for user in eda_data['username'].unique()]
filtered_data: np.ndarray = np.concatenate(filtered_data)    
eda_data['filt-EDA'] = filtered_data

Now, we can apply the normalization.

Again, to each user.

In [16]:
normalized_data: list[np.ndarray] = [
    normalize_signals(
        x=eda_data[eda_data['username'] == user]['filt-EDA'].values
    ) 
    for user in eda_data['username'].unique()
]
normalized_data: np.ndarray = np.concatenate(normalized_data)
eda_data['norm-EDA'] = normalized_data

Let's look at the changes!

In [17]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(14, 3))

Feature extraction¶

• Difficult to interpret the whole signal¶

• Analyse only some specific "features"¶

• Which features? Statistical elements: mean, std, median, etc.¶

• Also, some physiological features: number of EDA peaks, peak rise time, etc.¶

Do you extract features on the whole signal?¶

No¶

• We segment the signal into "sub-signals"¶

• Length of sub-signals appropriate for task ⬅ look at the literature¶

First, we segment the data.

Let's consider only one user for simplicity, as before.

In [18]:
eda_data_subset: pd.DataFrame = eda_data[
    eda_data['username'] == user_to_select
]

We shall use a window of 10 seconds.

The shortest EDA response is between 2 to 5 seconds. We consider longer to account for possible effects.

In [19]:
window_size_in_sec: int = 10
spl_rate: int = 4
window_size_in_sampling_rate: int = window_size_in_sec * spl_rate

The sampling rate is known from the manufacturer of the device (4Hz in this case).

In [20]:
starts: pd.Series = eda_data_subset[
                ::window_size_in_sampling_rate
            ]['timestamp']

ends: pd.Series = (starts +
                   pd.Timedelta(f"{window_size_in_sec}s") -
                   pd.Timedelta(f"{1/spl_rate}s"))
# we remove the last item since pandas will use <= by default when dealing with dates

We set the timestamp as the index of the DataFrame.

We do this since it is easier to slice it.

In [21]:
eda_data_subset = eda_data_subset.set_index('timestamp')
In [22]:
segmented_eda_data: list[pd.DataFrame] = [
    eda_data_subset.loc[start:end]
    for start, end in zip(starts, ends)]
# we print one example
display(segmented_eda_data[0].head(), len(segmented_eda_data[0]))

We now extract features.

For the sake of this tutorial, we are going to use the following limited list:

  • min
  • max
  • std
  • mean
  • number of EDA peaks
In [23]:
from neurokit2.eda import eda_peaks
from warnings import warn

def extract_features(data: np.ndarray, sampling_rate: int) -> pd.Series:
    """
    This method extracts hand-crafted features for EDA signals.
    
    Args:
        data (ndarray): input array of EDA data
        sampling_rate (int): sampling rate of the EDA signal

    Returns:
        (Series): dataframe with the features extracted as indexes

    """
    
    min_feat: float = np.min(data)
    max_feat: float = np.max(data)
    mean_feat: float = np.mean(data)
    std_feat: float = np.std(data)
    
    try:
        eda_peaks_result: dict[str, Any] = eda_peaks(
                data,
                sampling_rate=sampling_rate,
            )
    except ValueError as e:
            # NOTE: sometimes, when no peaks are detected, as ValueError is thrown by the
            # neurokit2 method. We solve this in a very simplistic way
        warn(f"Could not extract EDA peaks. Reason: {e}")
        eda_peaks_result: tuple[None, dict[str, Any]] = (
                None,
                dict(SCR_Peaks=[], SCR_Amplitude=[0]),
            )
    number_of_peaks_feat: int = len(eda_peaks_result[1]["SCR_Peaks"])
    return pd.Series([min_feat,max_feat,mean_feat,std_feat,number_of_peaks_feat], 
                        index=['Min', 'Max', 'Mean', 'Std', 'Num Peaks'])
In [24]:
extracted_features: list[pd.Series] = [

                     sampling_rate=spl_rate)
    for segment in segmented_eda_data]

Let's consider only our selected user's data.

We will re-segment the data and figure out which engagement label (1="engaged" or 0="not engaged") to apply.

    engagement_info['username'] == user_to_select
].copy()
engagement_info_subset['start'] = pd.to_datetime(
    engagement_info_subset['start']
)
engagement_info_subset['end'] = pd.to_datetime(
    engagement_info_subset['end']
)
In [34]:
def segmentation_with_label(eda_data: pd.DataFrame, 
                            start: pd.Timestamp, 
                            end: pd.Timestamp, 
                            label_df: pd.DataFrame) -> tuple[pd.DataFrame, int | float]:
    segment: pd.DataFrame = eda_data_subset.loc[start:end]
#         Due to the construction of the info dataframe, we have to iterate through all of the rows
# However, only one row will match the timestamps
    engagement_labels: list[int] = [
        row['engagement']
        for _, row in engagement_info_subset.iterrows()
        if (start >= row["start"]) and (end <= row["end"])]
    if len(engagement_labels) > 1:
        raise RuntimeError(f'Two rows of the info dataframes match the given segment')
    elif len(engagement_labels) == 0:
        label: float = np.nan
    else:
        label: int = engagement_labels[0]
    return segment, label

segmented_eda_data: list[pd.DataFrame] = [segmentation_with_label(
    eda_data_subset, 
    start, 
    end, 
    label_df=engagement_info_subset)
                                          for start, end in zip(starts, 
                                                                ends)]

Finally, we can show the distribution as before. In this case, we separate depending on the engagement level.

In [40]:
import seaborn as sns
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(10,3))
sns.histplot(ax=axs[0], data=extracted_features, x='Min', 
             hue='engagement')
extracted_features.plot.box(ax=axs[1], 
                            column='Min', 
                            by='engagement')
for ax in axs:
    ax.set_xlabel('Min normalized EDA')
plt.show()
